Intertwining artificial intelligence and efficiency: An empirical
analysis of AI focus and operational efficacy in Chinese listed firms
Qianru Li , Yuhao Zhang*
, Geumchul Um*
College of Business, Gachon University, South Korea
A R T I C L E I N F O
Keywords:
Artificial intelligence
Operational efficiency
Three-stage least squares (3SLS)
Emerging market
Firm disclosure
AI focus
Firm performance
Marketing metrics
A B S T R A C T
This study contributes to the literature on the relationship between artificial intelligence (AI)
focus and operational efficiency in three key ways: by emphasizing firms’ disclosure of their focus
on AI, by providing new evidence from an emerging market context distinct from developed
economies and evaluating the practical implications of AI focus through operational efficiency.
Using data on Chinese-listed firms from 2010 to 2023, we proposed simultaneous equation
models and estimated them using three-stage least squares (3SLS). The results revealed that AI
focus is not associated with improvements in gross operational efficiency but is negatively related
to net operational efficiency.
1. Introduction
Artificial intelligence (AI) is a key driver of economic transformation and innovation. As the world’s largest developing economy,
China has rapidly positioned AI as a central component of its national development strategy. Chinese firms are increasingly emphasizing
AI as part of their competitive positioning. However, the actual economic benefits and productivity gains from AI adoption
remain subject to debate (Damioli et al., 2021). Owing to a lack of expertise, technological complexity(Makarius et al., 2020), and
uncertainty regarding its realized value(Fountaine et al., 2019), the extent of actual AI usage in firms remains limited(Makarius et al.,
2020). In the face of these challenges, many firms disclose their focus on AI to gain market recognition. As operational efficiency is
fundamental to firm survival and financial performance(Mishra et al., 2022), it remains unclear whether an AI focus has been
translated effectively into improved operational outcomes, especially in emerging markets such as China.
This study investigates the dynamic relationship between firms’ focus on AI and operational efficiency in China. This study defines
AI focus as the degree to which firms devote attention to AI. Gross operational efficiency is firms’ ability to convert input resources into
sales. Net operational efficiency is the ability to translate sales into profit, evaluated across three dimensions: labor, sales, and marketing
inputs. Adopting the theoretical framework and empirical approach of Mishra et al. (2022), we employ a system of simultaneous
equations estimated using three-stage least squares (3SLS) while controlling for market structure and firm-level characteristics.
The results of this study reveal no significant evidence that AI focus is positively associated with gross operational efficiency.
However, AI focus is negatively related to net operational efficiency. These findings suggest that firms do not enhance productivity
through AI focus; instead, they may incur additional costs. This supports the view that AI-related disclosures in annual reports function
more as symbolic signaling mechanisms aimed at aligning with investor expectations rather than reflecting the actual implementation
of AI in business operations—consistent with prior findings that actual AI adoption remains limited(Makarius et al., 2020).
