This study contributes to the literature in three ways: (1) emphasizes firms’ disclosure of their focus on AI; (2) offers new empirical
evidence from an emerging market context distinct from that of developed economies; and (3) evaluates the practical value of AI focus
through the lens of operational efficiency. These findings offer meaningful insights for both corporate decision-makers and
policymakers.
2. Theoretical background and research questions
Artificial Intelligence has been shown to enhance customer experience(Huang and Rust, 2018), create business value
(Wamba-Taguimdje et al., 2020), and improve ESG performance(Chen et al., 2024). Based on AI-related disclosures in annual reports,
some studies have found positive effects on financial performance(Shiyyab et al., 2023) and green innovation efficiency in energy firms
(Wang et al., 2024b). However, some evidence suggests that such outcomes are not guaranteed(Canhoto and Clear, 2020). Many firms
invest considerably in AI but fail to realize the expected benefits(Fountaine et al., 2019; Makarius et al., 2020).
We adopt the economic and marketing framework proposed by Mishra et al. (2022) and first examine how AI affects firm inputs,
especially advertising expenditure and labor. Artificial Intelligence can enhance the precision of advertising targeting(Shan, 2024) and
increase the demand for skilled labor(Wang and Jiao, 2025; Wang et al., 2024a). As Mishra et al. (2022) noted, the relationship
between AI focus and asset utilization efficiency(ratio of sales to total assets) is theoretically ambiguous and depends on the relative
strength of AI in advertising and the number of employees. Since input alone does not guarantee efficiency and asset utilization efficiency
is only one part of the equation, this relationship is not treated as a core hypothesis but incorporated into the structural model
as part of our empirical estimation.
To systematically evaluate whether AI focus enhances operational outcomes, we further distinguish between gross and net operational
efficiency. Gross operational efficiency reflects firms’ ability to convert input resources into output. Given the complementarity
between AI and human capital(Wang and Jiao, 2025), we use sales per employee as the core indicator of productivity(Mishra et al.,
2022; Morbey and Reithner, 1990; Sartal et al., 2020; Zhu et al., 2024). In contrast, net operational efficiency captures a firm’s ability
to convert output into profitability. We assess this across three dimensions—labor, sales, and marketing inputs—drawing on Mishra
et al. (2022). In particular, we include net income per employee, return on sales, and return on marketing investments. Fig. 1 illustrates
the conceptual framework underpinning this study. Accordingly, we propose the following research questions:
RQ1: How does AI focus affect gross operational efficiency (sales per employee)?
RQ2: How does AI focus affect net operational efficiency (net income per employee, return on sales, and return on marketing
investments)?
3. Research design
3.1. Data collection
This study used panel data on listed Chinese firms covering all industries from 2010 to 2023. Following common practices in
corporate finance research(Huang and Luan, 2024; Li et al., 2024; Zhang et al., 2024), we excluded firms with ST, *ST, and PT statuses1
Financial and employment data were obtained from the CSMAR and WIND databases, respectively. The measure of AI focus is constructed
using a textual analysis of annual reports. A total of 73 AI-related keywords were scaled using the following formula (Yao
et al., 2024):
