4.2. Regression results
Table 3 reports the estimation results based on Equations (1) through (10). We find that AI focus has no significant effect on gross
operational efficiency (β =–10.988, p>0.1), but it exerts a significant negative effect on all three measures of net operational efficiency
(β =–54.701, p< 0.01; β =–0.272, p< 0.01; β =–11.248, p< 0.01). These results suggest that while firms increasingly
emphasize AI focus, this emphasis may not reflect actual implementation at the operational level. Importantly, our model controls for a
comprehensive set of firm-level characteristics and market concentration (HHI). Even after accounting for these factors, the negative
association between AI focus and net operational efficiency persists, suggesting that firms’ focus on AI may primarily serve as a market
signaling strategy, resulting in increased costs rather than enhanced profitability.
4.3. Robustness tests
To ensure the robustness of our findings, we employ two approaches.
First, we conducted a propensity score matching (PSM) analysis to mitigate potential self-selection bias. The firms were classified
into treatment and control groups based on whether their AI focus was above or below the median sample size. A 1-to-1 nearest-
neighbor matching method was applied using a caliper to match firms with similar characteristics.
