boundaries and offer a broader perspective of the common difficulties that global firms may encounter when adopting AI. The results
point to a critical issue for corporate leaders—how to shift from merely “talking about AI” to actually “using AI” meaningfully. For
managers, this means reducing dependence on AI as a promotional tool and strengthening technical capabilities and resource
alignment. For policymakers, these findings underscore the importance of promoting greater transparency in AI implementation and
designing incentives to support genuine adoption.
This study has several limitations. Owing to data constraints, we do not account for organizational readiness or digital maturity
levels, which may affect the link between AI focus and efficiency. Furthermore, the institutional and developmental differences between
countries and industries can lead to heterogeneous outcomes. Future research could distinguish between types of AI-related
disclosures—such as strategic vision versus technical implementation, explore cross-country contexts, quantify digital transformation
indicators, and uncover underlying mechanisms or contextual contingencies. These efforts will help advance a more
nuanced understanding of AI’s symbolic and substantive roles in corporate strategies and performance.
